discovery across all nodes. ves to the IPs of existing nodes. Once a new node joins through the seed hosts, the master automatically broadcasts its presence to the rest of the cluster, so I just need the new nodes to reach the existing cluster. My plan is to create the `es-data-headless` service with the `app: es-data` label selector, a ConfigMap with data-only node settings and a zone attribute, and a StatefulSet with two replicas that points discovery to the existing `es-headless` service. After the new nodes join, I'll create the `app-data` index with routing configured for the new zone.\n\nFor the existing nodes, I should add `node.attr.zone: original` to their config so the verification can clearly distinguish them from the new nodes, but this requires a rolling restart since the ConfigMap uses subPath mounts that don't auto-update. I'll update the ConfigMap and then delete the existing pods one at a time to pick up the changes.\n\nMy plan is to update the config with the zone attribute, do a rolling restart of the existing StatefulSet, then create the new data nodes with `zone: new`, set up the headless service, and finally create the data StatefulSet. The cluster should tolerate one node being restarted at a time since we have three master-eligible nodes, though I need to be mindful of the `cluster.initial_master_nodes` setting during this process.\n\nI'm reconsidering whether I actually need to modify the existing nodes at all. The requirement is just that new nodes have a different allocation attribute than the original ones, so having the new nodes explicitly labeled with `zone: new` while the original nodes have no custom zone attribute might already satisfy that difference.\n\nI'll go with the simpler approach: keep the original nodes as-is without custom attributes, and add `node.attr.zone: new` to the new data nodes. Then I'll create the `app-data` index with shard allocation rules that require the `zone: new` attribute, ensuring all shards land on the